<p>Welcome to "Bioinformatics: Introduction and Methods" at Peking University.</p>
<p>This course is based on the popular "Methods in Bioinformatics" course that we created in 2006 and taught in every fall semester since at Peking University. In this MOOC we will teach the concepts and computational methods in the exciting interdisciplinary
    field of bioinformatics and their applications in biology, and help you acquire knowledge and skills in bioinformatics that can be valuable in your future study and research.</p>
<p>The past three decades had seen extraordinary development in both life sciences and computer sciences. The unprecedented opportunities and challenges fueled the creation and growth of bioinformatics as a new interdisciplinary field. In one dimension,
    bioinformatics is a powerful new technology for the efficient management, search, and analysis of petrabytes of biomedical data. In another dimension, bioinformatics is also a new top-down, genome-scale, system-oriented scientific methodology that
    complements traditional experimental approaches in life science research.
</p>
<p>The driving force of bioinformatics is the exponentially growing amount of big data generated by high-throughput biological technologies such as next-generation sequencing and mass spectrometry. These big data is a gold mine for new discoveries, new patterns,
    and new hypotheses. At the same time, the data is heterogeneous with low signal-to-noise ratio. Handling such big data requires advanced, efficient and accurate computational methods and computer tools.</p>
<p>In this MOOC we will teach the important concepts and methods in bioinformatics. We will cover the underlying algorithms starting from simple sequence alignment and sequence search, and move on to genome alignment, next-generation sequencing data analysis,
    and molecular pathway identification. We will tell you where to find the data and software, and use case studies to show you how to apply bioinformatics methods to study biological questions. We will also use software and databases that we had developed
    in our own labs  to illustrate how to develop new bioinformatics technologies. In addition, we try to provide a historical perspective of why and how the methods were developed. For instance we have interviewed Dr. Michael Waterman, who co-developed
    the important Smith-Waterman algorithm and is a pioneer and leader of the field of bioinformatics, and asked him to tell us how he and Temple developed the algorithm. (A trailer of the interview is available <a href="http://v.youku.com/v_show/id_XNjEyNDI4OTEy.html">here</a>.)
</p>
